data.strength: I tried to be cooperative. At first I only contributed 15 coins at a time, then I started contributing all. data.fair: I suppose. I always wish I could receive more money, because inflation is killing me. I think it might also be interesting if you could give another bonus related to the amount of coins contributed over the course of the game, that isn't revealed until after the game has been completed.
data.feedback: I would love it my total amount of coins accumulated in the game could be directly translated into a dollar amount (100 coins = $1), so that the incentive to maximize coins would be that much greater. I would be interested to see an analysis of the specific game I played. It's interesting to see if a group can work together to maximize outcomes for each other, or if there's always gonna be that one guy who contributes nothing and benefits off of everyone else's work. A group can only have so many of that kind of person before the whole thing collapses. I liked that one player got removed for being idle, so our pot was only divided among 12 instead of 13. I might feel bad if they had been contributing, but they weren't, so it was nice to not have to share with them. I would also like it if there was another, secret, bonus based on how many coins were contributed over the course of the game. This would be an additional reward for those who kept contributing to the pot while watching others benefit off their generousity.

data.strength:
I was trying to create as many coins as possible and be as generous as possible and hope others would do the same. 

I tried to not reward people who didn't contribute 20, but I was generally overgenerous even when I wasn't being rewarded back, in order to try and create a lot of coins and hopefully spur on generosity in later rounds. 

Unfortunately it didn't really pay off, so I did start being less generous, but it was too late in the rounds to really punish the others' lack of generosity effectively.

In retrospect, I think I should have been more reciprocal, particularly in regard to how much others were spending on rewards. E.g. if others are awarding, 8, 8, and 12, I should award in that range, maybe 20 at most, and then tone it up/down based on how reciprocal they are round by round.

data.strength: The pot bonus was 8.1x, which is very high. In theory, if I contributed 20 coins to the pot, and even only 1 other person out of 12 contributed 20, that's 40 in the middle, times 8.1, which is 324. Divide this by the number of players, 13, and you get around 25. Therefore, if I contribute 20 coins, all I need is one other person out of 13 to contribute 20, or all I need is for the combined contribution of all 12 remaining players to be 20, and it would be worth it since I'm giving 20 and receiving 25. At that point, its' worth it too risk others not giving 20 coins. The multiplier of 8.1x was simply too high, and the benefit of getting 200+coins was way larger than the risk of losing any, which was almost impossible. There was some hidden meta, such as, if everyone else goes 20, in theory you should go 0, but the coins gained from such a strategy are so marginally small compared to the risk of other people going 0. Would you risk your 20 coins for a likely gain of 200 coins? The answer should be yes. That was my strategy. I gave 20 every round but 1 where I wanted to be cheeky.
data.fair: Yes, I do feel I was fairly compensated.

data.strength: At first, I wanted to punish people who had punished me, but then I decided that it made more sense to think mathematically and I felt like putting all my coins into the multiplier gave the best chance of maximising my returns.

I wanted to see whether the other team members would be generous or selfish to the public pot, and I was going to do the opposite to what they were doing to maximise my share. Then I saw most people were giving quite high amounts to the public pot, and thought I should contribute the same. Then I started deducting points from the people who were contributing low, and it seemed to make their contributions go up. data.strength: I was pretty sure the best case scenario would be if everyone put in as much money as they could and also gifted all their money to everyone.  Since gifting 3 gives the other person 4 it is a net gain if everyone does it, but I wasn't confident people would get that so I focused more on giving the 20 every time and tried out the gifting only a little to test the waters to see if people would reciprocate and to keep myself interested by mixing it up.  Once I figured that wasn't happening I stopped and just kept doing the 20 until around the halfway point.  I then stopped putting anything into the pot since that would reward me more and with it being already halfway through I thought it was less likely that everyone would start doing that as well and tank our overall rewards (so I can benefit without losing potential reward).  I also noticed I was getting 46 every round at that point which meant the group was being consistent with their choices and I wanted to see how long that went on for (kept up until the last round when someone else also didn't contribute to the pot).
